INSERT INTO instructions (instructions)
VALUES
('1. Placed sliced apples evenly in the pot of the Ninja Foodi. 2. In a small bowl, combine the sugar, flour, cinnamon, and nutmeg. 3. Evenly pour this over the apples. 4. In Food Processor, combine the oats, flour, brown sugar, baking powder, and baking soda. 5. Mix in the softened butter. Start with one stick to create crumble mixture. 6. This should be a crumble mixture. Evenly add this to the top of the apples. 7. Shut the lid that is attached to the Ninja Foodi. Bake for 40 minutes at 350 degrees. Serve warm with a side of vanilla ice cream.'),
('1. Peel, core, and slice apples in 1/4 inch slices. 2. Place apple slices, freshly squeezed lemon juice, and water in large stock pan. Heat to boiling and then reduce heat to medium. Simmer until apples are soft, stirring often, for approximately 35-40 minutes. 3. Remove from heat and add sugars and cinnamon. Stir well and pour into large bowl or storage container. NOTES- Less time for more chunky, around 30 mins. Less brown sugar for sweeter apples'),
('1. Place rub ingredients in a bowl and mix to combine. Rub all over brisket with hands. 2. Pour BBQ sauce ingredients in the slow cooker. Mix then add the brisket and press brisket into sauce. 3. Cook on low for 8-10 hours, high for 4-5 hours. 4. Remove brisket from slow cooker onto a baking tray. Drizzle a few tablespoons of pan drippings on the brisket. 5. Pour liquid from slow cooker into a sauce pan and simmer over medium high heat until it thickens to a sauce like consistency. 6. Oven Method: Meanwhile cook brisket in 400 degree oven for 5-10 minutes until it begins to brown a bit. Remove from oven and mop on BBQ sauce, cook for 5 minutes, turn over and repeat for 5-10 or until caramelized. Or do this on the BBQ grill on medium high heat. Cook time for caramelization may be shorter. Then remove. 7. Slice Brisket thinly across the grain and serve with BBQ sauce.'),
('1. Place meat in slow cooker. In a small bowl, mix together the flour, salt and pepper; pour over meat and stir to coat meat with flour mixture. Stir in the garlice, bay leaf, paprika, Worcestershire sauce, onion, beef broth, potatoes, carrots and celery. 2. Cover and cook on low setting for 10-12 hours or on high for 4-6 hours.'),
('1. Preheat oven to 250 degrees. 2. Mix sugar, cinnamon and salt together in a bowl. 3. Whisk egg white and water together in a seperate bowl until frothy. Toss pecans in the egg white mixture. Mix sugar mixture into pecan mixture until pecans are evenly coated. Spread coated pecans onto a baking sheet. 4. Bake in the preheated oven, stirring every 15 minutes until pecans are evenly browned, 1 hour.'),
('1. Slice steaks into strips before marinating. 2. Marinade steak in a ziplock bag with onion, soy, cumin, garlic and pepper. Sit for 20 minutes at room temperature. 3. While steak is sitting, prepare pico. Combine all ingredients in a medium bowl and set aside. 4. Using non-stick pan, set on high heat. Then sear steak, continue to cook until desired done. Assemble tacos.'),
('1. Heat broiler to high or oven to 500 degrees. Halve, peel and thinly slice onion. Mince a few slices for 2 T. Halve, core and thinly slice bell pepper. Drain pineapple. 2. Heat drizzle of olive oil in pan, medium heat. Add pepper and onion. Cook, stirring occasionally, 4-5 minutes. Season with salt and pepper. Add pineapple, stir until lightly brown, 2-3 minutes. Season with salt and pepper. Turn off heat, remove from pan and wipe pan. 3. Dice tomato. Roughly chop cilantro. Halve Lime. In bowl, combine minced onion, tomato, half of cilantro and squeeze of lime juice. Season with salt and pepper. 4. Pat dry chicken. Heat oil in pan, medium heat. Add chicken and spices. Cook, stirring until chicken is browned and cooked through, 4-6 minutes. Season with salt and pepper. Return veggie mix to pan along with squeeze of lime juice and remaining cilantro. Stir and shut off heat. 5. Rub one side of each tortilla with a drizzle of oil. Place tortillas, oiled sides down on baking sheet. Evenly sprinkle with half of mozzarella. Top with fllling then sprinkle with the remaining mozzarella. Fold tortillas in half. 6. Broil or bake quesadillas until golden brown on top, 1-2 minutes. Flip and repeat on opposite side. Cut into wedges. Serve with pico and sour cream.'),
('1. Preheat oven to 350 degrees. 2. In large bowl, beat butter, sugar, eggs and vanilla until light and fluffy. Combine the flour, cocoa, baking soda and salt; stir into the butter mixture until well blended. Mix in the chocolate chips. Drop by rounded teaspoonfuls onto ungreased cookie sheets. 3. Bake for 8-10 minutes in the preheated oven or just until set. Cool slightly on the the cookie sheets before transferring to wire racks to cool completely.'),
('1. Halve zucchini lengthwise, thin slices. Halve lime. In bowl combine mayonnaise and sweet chili sauce. Pit and small dice nectarine. Place in seperate bowl, add sugar and juice of one 1/2 Lime. Season with salt and pepper. Stir. 2. In medium pot, combine rice, pinch of salt and 1 C of water. Boil. Reduce heat to low, cover and cook, without stirring, 12-14 minutes. Turn off heat and fluff. Add nectarine (including liquid) and stir. Season with salt and pepper. 3. Medium pan, heat medium heat with oil. Add zucchini, cook without stirring 3-4 minutes. Season with salt and pepper. Add mustard seeds, stir occasionally 2-4 minutes. Turn off heat. Stir in lime juice. Season with salt and pepper. Transfer to plate. 4. Pat dry chicken. In bowl, chicken, salt and pepper, cornstarch and curry powder. In pan, heat oil medium heat. Once oil is hot enough that cornstarch sizzles, add chicken. Cook without stirring, 3-4 minutes. 5. Transfer chicken to bowl of chili/mayo. Stir to coat, season with salt and pepper and serve with rice.'),
('1. Preheat oven to 400 degrees. Line baking sheet with parchment paper. 2. Cut fish into 1oz pieces and generously salt. Combine flour and paprika in medium bowl. Crack and wisk eggs in seperate bowl. Dip fish in flour, then egg, then breadcrumbs making sure all sides are coated. Place on baking sheet and bake for 10 minutes until crispy. 3. Meanwhile, prepare slaw. Combine ingredients in medium bowl. Set aside. 4. Assemble tacos.'),
('1. Adjust rack to top position and preheat to 425 degrees. Thinly slice scallions, seperating greens and whites. Peel and mince ginger. 2. In large bowl, combine mayonnaise, sour cream, honey, 2 t of Soy Sauce and sriracha. Set aside. 3. In small pot, combine rice, 1 C of water and pinch of salt. Bring to boil then cover and reduce heat to low. Cook 15-18 minutes. Keep covered off heat until ready to serve. 4. In second large bowl, combine beef, bread crumbs, scallion whites, remaining soy sauce, salt and pepper. Form into 10-12 balls. 5. Place balls on one side of large baking sheet. Toss green beans on empty side of pan with oil, salt and pepper. Roast on top rack, 14-16 minutes. 6. Fluff rice with fork, season with salt and pepper. Divide between two plates. Carefully add balls to bowl with sauce; toss to coat. Top rice with balls and drizzle sauce. Serve green beans to the side and garnish with scallion greens.'),
('1. Preheat oven to 400 degrees. 2. Cut potatoes in half or quarters and place in a bowl with the olive oil, salt, pepper and garlic; toss until potatoes are well coated. Transfer the potatoes to a sheet pan and spread out into 1 layer. Roast in the oven for 45 minutes to 1 hour or until browned and crisp. Flip twice with a spatula during cooking in order to ensure even browning. 3. Remove potatoes from the oven, toss with parsley, season with salt and pepper to taste and serve hot.'),
('1. Heat oven to 350 degrees. 2. Cover bottoms of 3 (9inch) round pans with parchment; spray sides with cooking spray. Microwave chocolate and waterin large microwavable bowl on HIGH 1 1/2 - 2 minutes or until chocolate is almost completely melted, stirring after 1 minute. Stir until chocolate is completely melted. 3. Beat egg whites in small bowl with mixer on high speed until stiff peaks form; set aside. Combine flour, baking soda and salt. Beat butter and sugar in large bowl with mixer until light and fluffy. Add egg yolks, 1 at a time, beating well after each. Blend in melted chocolate and vanilla. Add flour mixture alternately with buttermilk, beating until well blended after each addition. 4. Add egg whites; stir gently until well blended. Pour into prepared pans. 5. Bake 30 minutes or until toothpick inserted in center comes out clean. Immediately run small spatula around cakes in pans. Cool cakes in pans 15 minutes. Remove from pans to wire racks; cool completely. Wisk egg yolks and milk in large saucepan until blended. Add sugar and butter; cook, stirring constatnly, over medium heat 12 minutes or until thickened and golden brown. Remove from heat. Add remaining ingredients; mix will. Cool to desired spreading consistency. 6. Prepare coconut-pecan filling/frosting: spread between cake layers and ontop of cake.'),
('1. Cut open avacado around the middle, take out pit and remove outer skin. Using fork, mash avacado until lumpy. Immediately add lime juice. Lime juice will preven avacado from browning. Mix in tomato and onion and then add cilantro, olive oil, salt and pepper gently. Chill for 5 minutes'),
('1. Place the cucumber in a colander in the sink and sprinkle kosher salt. Let sit and drain for 30 minutes. Dry thoroughly with paper towels, then chop very finely. 2. Combine cucumbers with the yogurt, garlic, lemon juice and dill. Refrigerate for at least 2 hours before serving. The sauce can be kept in the refrigerator in an airtight container for up to three days. 3. In a medium bowl, combin the ground lamb, salt, pepper and oregano leaves with your hands, mixing until all of the seasonings have been evenly distributed. Cover and refrigerate for at least 1 hour or overnight. 4. Preheat oven to 300 degrees. Place lamb mixture in food processor and add onion and garlic. Process until smooth puree is formed, 30 seconds to 1 minute, scraping down the sides of the bowl as necessary. 5. Line a rimmed baking sheet with aluminum foil. With moistened hands, shape the lamb mixture into a rectangle about 8 inches long and 5 inches wide. Bake until center of loaf reaches 155 degrees, 30-35 minutes. Remove from the oven and allow to rest for 15 minutes. 6. Adjust the oven rack to highest position and preheat broiler. Slice the loaf of lamb meat crosswise into very thin pieces (should be about 1/8 inches thick). Lay the strips on a rimmed baking sheet lined with aluminum foil and broil until edges are browned and crispy, 2-4 minutes. Be sure to keep an eye on it as broiler works quickly. 7. Warm up the bread in the microwave(30 seconds), on the stovetop or the oven. Top each with 1/4 C of tzatziki sauce, chopped tomatoes, slice onions and gyro meat. Wrap with foil and serve.'),
('1. Pour water into a large saucepan and bring to boil. Remove from heat and toss in the tea bags. Cover and let steep for 5 minutes. Remove tea bags and stir in sugar, cider, rum and 2 cinnamon sticks. Heat just to steaming, DO NOT BOIL. 2. Ladle hot cider into 6 mugs and drop 1/2 t of butter into each. Garnish with a cinnamon stick.'),
('1. Preheat oven to 350 degrees. 2. In medium bowl, combine milk, sour cream, lime juice and zest. Mix well and pour into crust. 3. Bake in preheated oven for 5-8 minutes until little tiny pinhole bubbles burst on the surface of the pie. DO NOT BROWN. Chill pie before serving. Garnish with lime slices and whipped cream.'),
('1. Preheat oven to 350 degrees. 2. In medium saucepan, whisk together 1 C of sugar, flour, cornstarch and salt. Stir in water, lemon juice and lemon zest. Cook over medium-high heat, stirring freqently until mixture comes to a boil. Stir in butter. Place egg yolks in a small bowl and gradually whisk in 1/2 C of hot sugar mixture. Whisk egg yolk mixture back into remaining sugar mixture. Bring to boil and continue to cook while stirring constantly until thick. Remove from heat. Pour filling into pie shell. 3. In a large glass or metal bowl, whip egg whites until foamy. Add sugar gradually and continue to whip until stiff peaks form. Spread meringue over pie, sealing the edges at the crust. 4. Bake in preheated oven for 10 minutes or until meringue is golden brown.'),
('1. Preheat oven to 400 degrees. Line baking sheet with parchment paper. 2. Drizzle corn with olive oil and a sprinkle of salt. Roast in oven for 10 minutes or until kernels turn gold. Mix mayo and chilli powder and brush on cob. Sprinkle cob with cheese, cilantro, zest and juice.'),
('1. Preheat oven to 450. Cut potatoes into wedges. Halve, peel and thinly slice onion. Thinly slice cheese. Quarter lime. In bowl, combine guacamole and juice from 2 lime wedges. 2. Place potato wedges in a bowl. Drizzle with oil and season. Toss to coat. Transfer to sheet pan. Roast 21-23 minutes, or until browned. Remove from oven. 3. Combine beef and season. Form mixture into patties. In pan of oil, medium heat, add patties and cook 3-4 minutes per side. Transfer to plate. 4. In pan, heat oil. Add onion and season. 4-5 or until browned and softened. Turn off heat. 5. Assemble! Bread, cheese, patty, onion, bread. Rinse pan. 6. In pan, oil in medium heat. Add patty melts. Cook, occasionally pressing down, 2-4 minutes. Transfer to cutting board, season then halve. Serve melts with potatoes and guacamole and lime wedges'),
('1. Make sure all of the ingredients are well chilled. Fill a large punch bowl with ice. Top with the cranberry juice, sparkling wine, apple cider, ginger ale, and rum. Stir gently to combine. Top with the orange slices and fresh cranberries.'),
('1. Add apples, oranges, and sugar to a large pitcher and muddle with a muddler or wooden spoon for 45 seconds. 2. Add orange juice and brandy and muddle again to combine for 30 seconds. 3. Add red wine and stir to incorporate, then taste and adjust flavor as needed. I added a bit more brandy, orange juice and brown sugar. Stir to combine. 4. Add ice and stir once more to chill. Serve as is, or with a bit more ice. Garnish with orange segments (optional). 5. Store leftovers covered in the refrigerator for up to 48 hours, though best when fresh. Notes: Top with seltzer'),
('1. Slice each chicken breast into two pieces lengthwise as if you were butterflying the breast open, but just cut through. Pound each piece between 2 pieces of parchment paper as this as possible using a mallet or the heel of your hand. Should be between about 1/2-inch (12mm) thick. Season both sides with a generous amount of salt. 2. Prepare the breading station in baking pans or shallow bowls. In the first, place the flour. In the second, whisk together the eggs and mustard. The last, combine the plain breadcrumbs, panko, sesame seeds, salt and pepper. 3. Heat air fryer to air crisp to 390 for 5 mins. Then spray both sides of chicken and inside of fryer. Then fry for 5 mins till doneness. 4. Place the breaded breast straight into the oil. Continue with the rest of the chicken. 5. Construct the sandwiches by smearing a very good amount of mayonnaise on both sides of the ciabatta. Place the schnitzel on the bread, top with the sumac slaw.'),
('1. Fill medium pot 3/4 with salted water. Cover and heat to boil. Cut green beans. Slice shallot. Chop one garlic, grate other. In bowl, combine mayonnaise and garlic paste. Season. 2. Pat dry steaks, season. In pan, drizzle olive oil in medium heat till hot. Add steaks, cook 6-8 minutes per side. Set aside. 3. Add green beans to boiled water, 2-3 minutes. Leaving water boiling, remove green beans and pat dry. In hot pan, drizzle olive oil and add shallot. Season. Cook, stir occasionally, 1-2 minutes, seperating layers until browned. Add green beans. Season and stir occasionally 1-2 minutes. Transfer to bowl. 4. Add gnocchi to boiled water. 2-3 minutes until floating then drain. 5. In hot pan, add 1 T olive oil till medium hot. Add gnocchi, no stir 2-3 minutes. Season. 6. Slice steak. Top with aoili. Serve'),
('1. Preheat oven to 450. Peel and large dice shallot. Peel carrots, halve crosswise. Halve radishes lengthwise. Medium dice potatoes. Combine in large bowl. 2. Line sheet pan with foil. In bowl, add rosemary, drizzle oil and season. Toss to coat. Transfer veggies to half of pan. 3. Pat dry pork. Transfer to other half of pan. Drizzle oil and season both sides. Roast 33-35 mins. Remobe from oven. Remove rosemary. Transfer pork to plate. 4. In bowl, combine syrup and mustard. Season. 5. Slice pork. Serve pork with veggies. Top with sauce'),
('1. Seperate Kale leaves and cut thin. Peel garlic, flatten with flat side of knife. Quarter, core and thinly slice pear. Medium dice peppers. 2. In large bowl, combine salsa, fromage, and 1/2 t of olive oil. Season with salt and pepper. Add sliced kale. Massage in marinade. 3. In medium pan, heat 1/2 t of olive oil till medium hot. Add breadcrumbs and smashed garlic. Season salt and pepper. Cook, stirring frequently, 2-3 minutes or until breadcrumbs are browned and toasted. Transfer to bowl, discard garlic. Add parmesan cheese and stir to combine. 4. Pat chicken dry, season. Medium pan, heat 1/2 t of olive oil till medium hot. Cook chicken 3-5 minutes per side. Turn off heat. 5. In bowl of kale, add pear and peppers. Toss to combine. Season. Serve salad topped with chicken and breadcrumbs.'),
('1. Prepare your tomatoes by washing in plain water. Cut them in half or quarters and add to your saucepots. 2. In a large frying pan, sauté onions and garlic in olive oil until soft. Add to the saucepans with the prepared tomatoes. Simmer on low heat, stirring occasionally so to prevent sticking. 3. As the tomatoes simmer, they will release their juices. After the tomatoes and the vegetables are soft, turn off the heat and allow the sauce to cool. 4. Run the cooled tomato sauce through Food Strainer or Food Mill to remove skins, seeds, and to smooth out the sauce. 5. Return the strained tomato sauce to the saucepan(s) to cook down further to thicken the sauce. Add oregano, bay leaves, pepper, sugar, and crushed red pepper. If you are using multiple pots, roughly divide the ingredients for each pot. All the ingredients will be combined into one pot as the sauce cooks down. Simmer over low heat with the cover vented so the excess moisture evaporates. As the sauce reduces, combine it into one pot. Use your ladle to avoid splashing. 6. Once the volume is reduced by half, your tomato sauce should be nice and thick. Use a clean spoon and taste the sauce. Add salt and stir in. Taste again. Add more salt if needed. Keep the sauce warm over low heat. 7. Prepare your jars and lids by washing in warm, soapy water and rinsing thoroughly. Place jar rack into water bath canner, set jars in the canner, add water, and boil jars for 10 minutes to sterilize. Warm your lids in a small pot over low heat. Keep jars and lids warm until ready to use. 8. Spread a kitchen towel on the counter. Use your jar lifter to remove warm jars from canner, drain, and line up on the towel. Add citric acid or bottled lemon juice to each jar. For pints, add 1/4 teaspoon of citric acid or 1 Tablespoon of bottled lemon juice to each jar. For quarts, add 1/2 teaspoon citric acid or 2 Tablespoons of bottled lemon juice to each jar. 9. Use your canning ladle and funnel and add tomato sauce to warm jars leaving 1/2-inch headspace. Wipe the rims. Use your magnetic lid lifter to lift lids out of the warm water, center lid on the jar, and screw on band until it is fingertip tight. 10. Using a jar lifter, place jars carefully into canner leaving space in between them. Once jars are all in canner, adjust the water level so it is at least one inch above the jar tops. Add more boiling water if needed so the water level is at least one inch above the jar tops. When adding water, use the hot water from the small pot your lids were in. Pour the water around the jars and not directly onto them. 11. Cover the canner and bring to boil over high heat. Once water boils vigorously, process pints for 35 minutes and quarts for 40 minutes at altitudes of less than 1,000 ft. (adjust processing time for your altitude if necessary). 12. When processing time is complete, turn off heat and allow the canner to cool down and settle for about 10 minutes. Spread a kitchen towel on the counter; remove the cover by tilting lid away from you so that steam does not burn your face. Use a jar lifter to lift jars carefully from canner and place on the towel. Allow the jars to cool for 12 to 24-hours. You should hear the satisfactory “ping” of the jar lids sealing. 13. After 12 to 24-hours, check to be sure jar lids have sealed by pushing on the center of the lid. The lid should not pop up. If the lid flexes up and down, it did not seal. Refrigerate jar and use up within a few days. 14. Remove the screw on bands and wash the jars. Label and date the jars. Store your jars in a cool, dark place and use within 12 months. Yields about 6-7 pint jars or 3-4 quarts depending on how much the sauce reduces.'),
('1. Combine juices, simple syrup and whiskey in a small pitcher. Stir gently'),
('1. Place peeled and pitted peaches in blender with a few splashes of wine. Puree until smooth. 2. In large beverage dispenser or jug, stir together peach puree, remaining wine, brandy, orange juice, pineapple juice and triple sec. Add apples, oranges and sliced peaches. Refrigerate 24 – 48 hours. Stir in soda or seltzer just before serving.'),
('1. Grate zucchinis on large side of grater. Also cheese if necessary. Thinly slice scallions, seperating green and white. Quarter lime. 2. In large pan, heat oil medium. Add zucchini, season and cook stirring frequently 2-3 mins. Transfer to large bowl, add raisins, cheese, sliced white bottoms, juice of 1/4 lime. 3. Place tortilla on flat surface. Top one half of each with filling. Fold over. Heat pan with oil, medium heat. Add quesadilla. Cook 2-4 mins per side. Transfer to plate, season. 4. Fry eggs. 5. In bowl, add sour cream and juice of 1/4 lime juice and drizzle oil. Stir and season. Serve quesadillas with fried egg on top. Garnish green scallions. Remaining lime wedges on side.');
